

ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE AND THE ROADS THAT LEAD TO ROME

Infrastructure, Decentralisation, and the Paradox of Corporate Self-Irrelevance

White Paper No. 61-Δ
Classification: Publicly Obvious, Strategically Inconvenient
Prepared by: Office of Imperial Logistics Failure, Institute for Distributed Consequence Studies
Date: Unduly Contemporary

⸻

Executive Summary

This paper argues that the long-run success condition of any artificial intelligence company contains an internal contradiction severe enough to qualify as a structural law.

To succeed, an AI company must distribute capability outward. It must make intelligence cheaper, easier, more accessible, more legible, more modular, and more widely usable across society. It must convert difficult acts into ordinary ones. It must turn expertise into interface, abstraction into product, and cognition into infrastructure.

But the moment this process succeeds at sufficient scale, the strategic exclusivity of the company begins to weaken.

The logic is straightforward. A system that centralises power by building roads also creates routes by which others may reach, imitate, study, replace, fragment, localise, and eventually route around that centre. Rome built roads to extend command, move grain, project law, coordinate taxation, and deploy force. Those same roads also made Rome reachable. Infrastructure does not only project power outward. It makes power accessible inward.

Artificial intelligence platforms now occupy an analogous position. They are not merely software vendors or research labs. They are builders of cognitive roads: pathways through which reasoning, synthesis, automation, simulation, design, classification, generation, and strategic coordination become increasingly available to wider populations. At first, all roads lead to the platform. Users depend on its models, compute, interface, distribution, and permissions. But over time, those same roads teach the world how the journey works.

The user learns prompting. The company learns orchestration. The competitor learns replication. The developer learns substitution. The institution learns procurement and local deployment. The open-source community learns compression. The market learns which functions matter and which merely look expensive.

Thus the paradox emerges:

A successful AI company universalises the very capabilities that once justified its centrality.

Its highest civilisational success condition is therefore also the beginning of its corporate self-irrelevance.

This paper does not argue that such firms vanish overnight, nor that decentralisation is instant, nor that all centres collapse theatrically. It argues something more precise: that the distribution of intelligence infrastructure carries with it a built-in tendency toward peripheralisation. The more effectively the centre teaches the world to operate through machine-mediated cognition, the less metaphysically necessary that centre remains.

In this sense, the mature AI company faces the Roman problem. It seeks to rule through roads. But roads do not remain loyal merely because they were funded at origin.

