1. Introduction

On the Strategic Hazard of Building the Thing Everyone Can Then Use Against You

Modern technological firms tend to describe success using the language of adoption, scale, integration, ubiquity, ecosystem expansion, and embeddedness. Their aspiration is not merely to sell products, but to become infrastructure. Infrastructure is the corporate form of divinity: invisible when functioning, indispensable when absent, and difficult for ordinary society to imagine replacing.

Artificial intelligence companies now openly pursue this condition. They do not seek only to sell chat systems, assistants, coding tools, search overlays, enterprise automation layers, or model access. They seek to become the cognitive substrate through which work is organised, creativity is accelerated, software is written, research is drafted, customer service is automated, media is generated, and institutions are coordinated.

This is an imperial ambition whether or not the firms involved enjoy the phrase.

To become infrastructure is to become Rome.

Rome was not powerful merely because it possessed soldiers. It was powerful because it possessed roads, granaries, law, administration, language, logistics, tax flows, symbolic legitimacy, and systems of movement. Rome did not dominate by standing still in ornamental self-regard. It dominated because it built pathways across distance through which command could travel.

But such systems contain a fatal ambiguity. The road built for tribute also carries traffic in the other direction. The route created for administration also carries imitation. The infrastructure constructed to extend centrality simultaneously reduces the mystery of the centre.

This paper proposes that artificial intelligence companies now face the same structural problem.

If they fail to distribute capability, they remain marginal.
If they partially distribute capability, they remain useful but contested.
If they fully distribute capability, they erode the exclusive necessity of their own position.

The result is not a cinematic collapse, but a historical pattern: the centre wins by teaching the periphery how to stop needing the centre.

