2. Definitional Clarification

What It Means to Say AI Companies Are Building Roads

The argument of this paper depends on a specific understanding of infrastructure.

A road is not merely a physical object. It is a standardised channel of movement that reduces friction between origin and destination. It allows goods, people, instructions, symbols, obligations, and methods to travel more reliably than before.

In this sense, roads are not limited to stone. They may also take the form of protocols, interfaces, APIs, standards, supply chains, training systems, cloud architectures, legal templates, payment rails, developer ecosystems, and shared cognitive workflows.

Artificial intelligence companies are therefore building roads when they do any of the following:
	•	standardise human interaction with machine reasoning,
	•	reduce the cost of drafting, coding, synthesis, and analysis,
	•	teach millions of users how to decompose tasks into model-compatible structures,
	•	provide reusable APIs for generation, classification, retrieval, orchestration, and action,
	•	familiarise firms with model-driven workflows,
	•	create marketplaces of agents, toolchains, plug-ins, and automations,
	•	make previously elite capacities feel normal, repeatable, and menu-driven.

The key term here is legibility.

Before infrastructure, function is local, opaque, artisanal, and difficult to scale.
After infrastructure, function becomes visible, reproducible, transportable, and open to appropriation.

An AI platform does not merely perform tasks. It teaches a civilisation how those tasks may be decomposed, delegated, parameterised, benchmarked, and purchased.

This is not a side effect. It is the business model.

That is why the metaphor of roads is more accurate than the metaphor of products. Products are consumed. Roads are used to go elsewhere.

