4. The Early Stage of Centralisation

Why All Roads Initially Lead to the Model Provider

At the beginning of a capability revolution, centralisation is natural.

The frontier model company has the compute, the research staff, the training data pipelines, the optimisation expertise, the deployment stack, the capital base, the distribution partnerships, and the public legitimacy. It occupies the mountain because mountains are initially expensive.

Users therefore depend on the centre for reasons that are not imaginary:
	•	frontier capability is genuinely scarce,
	•	training large models is costly,
	•	inference infrastructure requires capital,
	•	evaluation frameworks are immature,
	•	developer tooling clusters around the leading providers,
	•	enterprise buyers prefer vendors that appear stable,
	•	the consumer market follows visible convenience.

This is the phase in which “all roads lead to Rome” is most visibly true.

The user goes to the model provider for reasoning.
The startup goes there for API access.
The enterprise goes there for procurement confidence.
The investor goes there for narrative concentration.
The regulator goes there because that is where scale appears to live.
The public goes there because central brands reduce uncertainty.

This early stage produces a familiar illusion: that dominance at the infrastructure layer can be indefinitely preserved simply by continuing to scale the same advantages.

But centralisation is not itself the endpoint. It is the launching condition.

The company must now justify its existence not merely by possessing intelligence, but by diffusing it. It must move from scarcity to ubiquity. It must get the road used.

That is where the contradiction begins.

