6. Legibility and Demystification

A Capability That Can Be Used Repeatedly Can Be Understood Incrementally

The strongest centres in history have often benefited from opacity. Their methods were difficult to inspect, their production systems difficult to imitate, their legitimacy difficult to contest without entering domains controlled by the centre itself.

Artificial intelligence companies are moving in the opposite direction.

They must make their systems legible enough to use.
To use them repeatedly, users must understand them at least partially.
To integrate them deeply, organisations must model their strengths, weaknesses, constraints, failure modes, and cost structures.
To compete with them, others must only learn the functions worth separating from the mystique.

Each of these steps reduces strategic opacity.

The user learns that not all intelligence requires a frontier model.
The enterprise learns that many workflows depend more on integration than raw benchmark supremacy.
The developer learns that task-specific systems can outperform general systems on commercial relevance.
The open-source ecosystem learns that smaller, specialised, or local models can address meaningful fractions of demand.
The regulator learns where the real chokepoints are.
The market learns which aspects of the centre were expensive necessity and which were theatrical premium coating.

The result is a demystification curve.

At first, the model appears magical.
Then it appears powerful.
Then it appears useful.
Then it appears understandable.
Then it appears decomposable.
Then it appears substitutable in parts.

A platform becomes most vulnerable when its methods become ordinary.

This is not because the platform is weak, but because ordinary things are hard to monopolise forever.

