9. On the False Dream of Permanent Tollbooths

Why “Owning the Layer” Is Harder Than Boards Think

Executive strategy frequently imagines infrastructure in static terms. Build the platform. Own the layer. Control the route. Monetise the flow. Become indispensable. Sit at the centre indefinitely like a benevolent spreadsheet deity collecting recurring revenue from everyone passing through.

This fantasy survives because it confuses being early at a chokepoint with possessing eternal rights over the function performed there.

History does not support this confidence.

Search became background.
Cloud became contested utility.
Compute became layered abstraction.
Open standards neutralised proprietary ambitions repeatedly.
Software categories that once appeared sovereign became procurement line items.
Communication platforms that imagined themselves permanent became interchangeable under pressure.

The pattern is not that valuable layers vanish. It is that they lose sacred status.

AI companies may indeed retain vast influence, revenue, and technical importance. But retaining importance is not the same as retaining irreplaceable singularity. Once a function becomes infrastructural, the market, the state, the enterprise, and the wider technical ecosystem all develop interests in reducing exposure to a single centre.

This is rational.

No society wants its cognitive metabolism fully hostage to one vendor forever.
No major institution wants permanent epistemic tenancy under a corporation without alternatives.
No developer ecosystem wants a single command point for all thought-adjacent interfaces.
No state with any self-respect wants irreversible dependence on external intelligence utilities.

Thus, even without ideological commitment to decentralisation, decentralisation emerges as a structural pressure.

The road that carries tribute also carries exit strategies.

