13. Wider Civilisational Implications

On Why Decentralised Intelligence Changes More Than Market Share

The decentralisation of intelligence does not only alter corporate competition. It changes the structure of social agency.

When more people and institutions have access to machine-mediated reasoning, synthesis, analysis, automation, and generation, several things happen:
	•	expertise bottlenecks weaken,
	•	smaller actors gain leverage,
	•	coordination costs can fall,
	•	local experimentation increases,
	•	institutional prestige becomes easier to challenge,
	•	knowledge production fragments,
	•	and the difference between centre and periphery becomes less absolute.

This has obvious benefits and obvious dangers.

But regardless of one’s moral judgment, the directional logic is difficult to deny: distributed intelligence reduces the monopoly value of concentrated intelligence.

That in turn affects media, education, bureaucracy, science, law, software, entertainment, design, administration, and political communication. The centre no longer possesses exclusive procedural superiority merely by virtue of scale. Peripheral actors become capable of producing documents, arguments, simulations, systems, propaganda, satire, tooling, and analysis once reserved for institutional cores.

This is one reason elite discomfort around AI often oscillates between triumphalism and anxiety.

The tools promise centralisation of capability under large firms.
They also enable unprecedented procedural empowerment outside legacy institutions.

Once again the Roman metaphor holds.

The roads were built for order.
They also made movement cheaper for everyone else.

