14. Objections

What This Paper Does Not Claim

For clarity, this paper does not claim the following:

It does not claim that every AI company becomes worthless.
It does not claim that decentralisation occurs instantly.
It does not claim that open systems automatically outperform central ones.
It does not claim that the centre disappears the moment the periphery gains tools.
It does not claim that all infrastructure companies collapse under their own success.

Rather, it claims something narrower and stronger:
	1.	AI companies succeed by diffusing cognitive capability.
	2.	Diffused capability increases legibility, familiarity, and local competence.
	3.	Those conditions systematically reduce the exclusive necessity of the original centre.
	4.	Therefore, the long-run success of the AI company tends to weaken the uniqueness that once justified its central dominance.

This is not prophecy. It is structural logic.

The exact pace depends on regulation, capital costs, open-source development, hardware economics, procurement norms, technical breakthroughs, market design, and state intervention. But the direction of pressure remains.

The centre can delay the consequences of roads.
It cannot fully abolish the fact that roads permit travel.

